---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import StructuredData from '../../components/StructuredData.astro';

const comparisonData = {
  date: 'January 20, 2025',
  tool1: {
    name: 'Webflow',
    slug: '/comparisons/framer-vs-webflow'
  },
  tool2: {
    name: 'WordPress',
    slug: '/reviews/10web'
  }
};

const quickVerdict = {
    webflow: 'Best for designers who want visual control',
    wordpress: 'Best for content sites and e-commerce',
    winner: 'Webflow for design/control, WordPress for flexibility/ecomm'
};

---

<Layout title="Webflow vs WordPress: Designer Platform vs Content CMS">

  <StructuredData
    type="WebPage"
    data={{
      name: 'Webflow vs WordPress: Designer Platform vs Content CMS',
      description: 'Webflow is a visual design platform that lets you build without code. WordPress is a content management system powering 40% of websites. One\'s for designers, one\'s for content. Here\'s the breakdown.',
      url: 'https://aiwebsitebuilders.com/comparisons/webflow-vs-wordpress'
    }}
  />

  <section class="relative overflow-hidden bg-[#FFF8F0]">
    <div class="absolute top-0 right-0 w-[45%] h-full opacity-[0.04]" style="background-image: repeating-linear-gradient(45deg, #F5521A 0px, #F5521A 1px, transparent 1px, transparent 12px);"></div>
    <div class="absolute bottom-0 left-0 w-32 h-32 bg-[#F5521A]/5 rounded-tr-[100px]"></div>

    <div class="container mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 max-w-7xl relative">
      <div class="py-12 md:py-16 lg:py-20">
        <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto space-y-6">

          <div class="inline-flex items-center gap-3 px-4 py-3 bg-white border-[3px] border-[#F5521A] shadow-[0_4px_0_0_rgba(245,82,26,0.3)]">
            <div class="flex gap-2">
              <span class="w-2 h-2 bg-[#F5521A] rotate-45"></span>
              <span class="w-2 h-2 bg-[#F5521A] rotate-45" style="animation-delay: 0.15s"></span>
              <span class="w-2 h-2 bg-[#F5521A] rotate-45" style="animation-delay: 0.3s"></span>
            </div>
            <span class="text-xs font-black tracking-widest text-gray-800" style="font-family: 'Space Mono', monospace;">
              {comparisonData.date} · COMPARISON
            </span>
          </div>

          <h1 class="text-4xl sm:text-5xl md:text-6xl lg:text-7xl font-black leading-[0.9] tracking-tight text-gray-900">
            <span class="block">Webflow vs WordPress:</span>
            <span class="block text-[#F5521A] mt-2">Designer vs Content</span>
          </h1>

          <div class="max-w-2xl">
            <p class="text-lg sm:text-xl text-gray-800/95 font-medium leading-relaxed">
              Webflow is a visual design platform—build what you see, pixel-perfect control, no code. WordPress is a content management system—40% of the web, plugin ecosystem, built for blogs and e-commerce. Different tools for different needs.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <main class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
    <article class="px-6 py-16 lg:py-24">
      <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
        <div class="bg-[#F5521A]/5 border-l-4 border-[#F5521A] p-6 my-8">
          <p class="text-gray-900">
            <strong>The one-sentence answer:</strong><br />
            Use Webflow if you're a designer who wants visual control and custom interactions.<br />
            Use WordPress if you're building a content site, blog, or e-commerce store.<br /><br />
            Webflow wins on design. WordPress wins on flexibility and ecosystem.
          </p>
        </div>

        <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-black text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6 flex items-center gap-3">
          <div class="w-1 h-8 bg-[#F5521A]"></div>The fundamental difference
        </h2>
        <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Webflow is a visual design platform. You design in the browser—drag, drop, style visually. The code is generated automatically. It's built for designers who want pixel-perfect control without touching code.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          WordPress is a content management system. You pick a theme, customize with settings, add plugins for functionality. It's built for content—blogs, news sites, e-commerce. 60,000 plugins extend functionality. Any WordPress developer can help.
        </p>

        <div class="my-8 p-6 bg-gray-100 border-[3px] border-gray-300">
          <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 text-sm">
            <div>
              <div class="text-gray-600 mb-2">Webflow:</div>
              <p class="text-gray-900">{quickVerdict.webflow}</p>
            </div>
            <div>
              <div class="text-gray-600 mb-2">WordPress:</div>
              <p class="text-gray-900">{quickVerdict.wordpress}</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-600 mt-4 pt-4 border-t border-gray-300">
            <strong>Verdict:</strong> {quickVerdict.winner}
          </p>
        </div>

        <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-black text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6 flex items-center gap-3">
          <div class="w-1 h-8 bg-[#F5521A]"></div>Quick comparison
        </h2>
        <div class="overflow-x-auto my-8">
          <table class="w-full text-left border-collapse">
            <thead>
              <tr class="border-b border-gray-300">
                <th class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-600 font-medium">Metric</th>
                <th class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-900 font-black">Webflow</th>
                <th class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-900 font-black">WordPress</th>
                <th class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-600 font-medium">Winner</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="border-b border-gray-300">
                <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-600">Design control</td>
                <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-900">Pixel-perfect visual</td>
                <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-900">Theme-based</td>
                <td class="py-3 px-4 text-green-600 font-medium">Webflow</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-gray-300">
                <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-600">E-commerce</td>
                <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-900">Webflow Ecommerce</td>
                <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-900">WooCommerce</td>
                <td class="py-3 px-4 text-green-600 font-medium">WordPress</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-gray-300">
                <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-600">PageSpeed</td>
                <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-900">85-95</td>
                <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-900">60-80 (unoptimized)</td>
                <td class="py-3 px-4 text-green-600 font-medium">Webflow</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-gray-300">
                <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-600">Plugin ecosystem</td>
                <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-900">Integrations only</td>
                <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-900">60,000+ plugins</td>
                <td class="py-3 px-4 text-green-600 font-medium">WordPress</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-gray-300">
                <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-600">Learning curve</td>
                <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-900">Steep</td>
                <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-900">Medium</td>
                <td class="py-3 px-4 text-green-600 font-medium">WordPress</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-600">Monthly cost</td>
                <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-900">$23-212</td>
                <td class="py-3 px-4 text-gray-900">$5-50</td>
                <td class="py-3 px-4 text-green-600 font-medium">WordPress</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-black text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6 flex items-center gap-3">
          <div class="w-1 h-8 bg-[#F5521A]"></div>Where Webflow wins
        </h2>

        <h3 class="text-xl font-black text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4">Visual design control</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Webflow's visual editor is unmatched. Design pixel-perfect layouts, create custom animations, build interactions—all visually. WordPress requires themes, page builders, or custom code. For designers who hate code, Webflow is paradise.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-xl font-black text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4">Animations and interactions</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Scroll animations, hover effects, page transitions—Webflow excels. Create complex interactions visually. WordPress needs plugins or custom code for advanced animations. If your site needs premium interactions, Webflow wins.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-xl font-black text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4">Clean code output</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Webflow generates clean HTML/CSS/JS. No theme bloat, no unused plugins. WordPress sites accumulate plugin bloat—themes load unused CSS, plugins add JavaScript bloat. Webflow sites are leaner by default.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-black text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6 flex items-center gap-3">
          <div class="w-1 h-8 bg-[#F5521A]"></div>Where WordPress wins
        </h2>

        <h3 class="text-xl font-black text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4">E-commerce</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          WooCommerce dominates e-commerce on WordPress. Product variants, inventory, shipping zones, tax calculation, 60+ payment gateways, extensions for everything. Webflow Ecommerce exists but WooCommerce is far more mature.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-xl font-black text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4">Plugin ecosystem</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          60,000+ plugins. Need memberships? There's a plugin. Need forums? bbPress. Need SEO? Yoast. Need literally anything? There's probably a plugin. Webflow has integrations but can't match WordPress's extensibility.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-xl font-black text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4">Content management</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          WordPress was built for content. Categories, tags, authors, comments, RSS, editorial workflow, revisions—everything a content site needs. Webflow has a CMS but it's not as deep as WordPress for content-heavy sites.
        </p>

        <h3 class="text-xl font-black text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4">Developer availability</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Any WordPress developer can help. There are millions of them. Webflow developers are fewer and more expensive. If you need to hand off work or hire help, WordPress wins on talent availability.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-black text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6 flex items-center gap-3">
          <div class="w-1 h-8 bg-[#F5521A]"></div>So which should you use?
        </h2>

        <h3 class="text-xl font-black text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4">Choose Webflow if:</h3>
        <ul class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          <li>You're a designer who wants visual control</li>
          <li>Your site needs premium animations/interactions</li>
          <li>You don't need complex e-commerce</li>
          <li>You want clean code without bloat</li>
          <li>Budget allows for higher hosting costs</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 class="text-xl font-black text-gray-900 mt-8 mb-4">Choose WordPress if:</h3>
        <ul class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          <li>You're building an e-commerce store</li>
          <li>You need plugin extensibility</li>
          <li>You're building a content-heavy site</li>
          <li>You want affordable hosting options</li>
          <li>You need easy access to developers</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-black text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6 flex items-center gap-3">
          <div class="w-1 h-8 bg-[#F5521A]"></div>Bottom line
        </h2>
        <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Webflow is for designers—visual control, custom interactions, clean code. WordPress is for content and commerce—extensible, familiar, massive ecosystem.<br /><br />
          For portfolios, marketing sites, agency sites—Webflow's design capabilities shine. For e-commerce, blogs, news sites—WordPress can't be beat. The mistake is choosing based on hype instead of your actual needs.
        </p>

        <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-4 my-12">
          <a href="/comparisons/framer-vs-webflow" class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-6 py-3 bg-white border-[3px] border-gray-300 text-gray-900 font-medium hover:border-[#F5521A] hover:text-[#F5521A] transition-colors">
            Compare Framer vs Webflow
          </a>
          <a href="/comparisons/10web-vs-wordpress" class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-6 py-3 bg-white border-[3px] border-gray-300 text-gray-900 font-medium hover:border-[#F5521A] hover:text-[#F5521A] transition-colors">
            Compare 10Web vs WordPress
          </a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </article>
  </main>

</Layout>
